<title type="html"><![CDATA[Big Bird's Hide and Speak sample compression]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8675&amp;p=91056#p91056"><![CDATA[
Now I am getting a bit of a better understanding of how these PCM-based speech engines work.  I've got the jist of how the sample playback works, but it is animating the character's mouth that I am wondering about.<br /><br />Of course, accurate lip synching is not an overall necessity, considering that the sample playback requires 100% CPU attention.  I mean, in Sesame Street Countdown, when the Count says, "'Ah, 'ah, 'ah! Find [number]," his mouth only opens three times.  I'd love to find out how Hide &amp; Speak manages to keep Big Bird's mouth moving during smaple playback.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4958">NEStegg</a> — Wed Mar 07, 2012 5:14 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
